        <name>19.2.9.4 First Order DE Ex3</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Find the general solution of the equation \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}t} + (\tan t)y = \cos t\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(y =\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] \(+ C\cos t\). [[feedback:prt1]] &lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;We are given the equation \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}t} + (\tan t)y = \cos t\). This equation is already in standard form. The coefficient in front of \(y\) is \(\tan t\). So the integrating factor is \[e^{\int \tan t \ \mathrm{d}t} = e^{\int \frac{\sin t}{\cos t} \ \mathrm{d}t} = e^{-\log(\cos t)} = -\frac{1}{\cos t}.\]&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Multiply the standard form of the equation by the integrating factor to get \[ \frac{1}{\cos t} \dfrac{\mathrm{d}y}{\mathrm{d}t} + \dfrac{\sin t}{\cos^2 t}y = 1.\] Recognise that this is now exact and construct an integral \[ \frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}t}\left(
    \frac{1}{\cos t}y \right) = 1 \iff \frac{1}{\cos t}y = \int 1 \ \mathrm{d}t.\] &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Integrating gives \[ \frac{1}{\cos t}y = t + C\] which implies \[ y = t\cos t + C\cos t.\]&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
